<TITLE> Italian right leads in early results of Rome vote </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ROME, April 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Early results from a runoff vote for Rome's mayor on Monday put an ally of prime minister-elect Silvio Berlusconi ahead as the right bid to conquer the capital for the first time since Benito Mussolini's rule in 1943. Results posted on Rome townhall's website, from just over a quarter of polling stations in the city, showed Gianni Alemanno of the post-fascist National Alliance party winning 52.7 percent of the vote. His rival Francesco Rutelli, a former Rome mayor from the centre-left Democratic Party, had 47.3 percent. Victory in Rome would be an unexpected bonus for Berlusconi, whose centre right overwhelmingly won an April 13-14 national election and already rules the financial capital in the north, Milan. The Italian capital has been run by the centre left for most of the past 30 years and continuously since 1993. Its outgoing mayor, Walter Veltroni, challenged Berlusconi for the prime ministership but was decisively defeated, like Rutelli in 200
